1. e4 e5 { The idea of a complete repertoire for White is not new and having done a few massive courses on Chessable for the black pieces I realized it was now the right time for me to do one.  My vision for the Lifetime Repertoire for White was to give you something that could actually last you a lifetime. I believe the concrete moves down the long variations are replaceable and possible to update, but the framework of the whole repertoire had to be healthy and ambitious enough so that there is that room for the replacements and the updates.  My idea is that if one of the suggestions I give, somewhere on move 20 can be neutralized, there would be room for you to deviate for your next game while staying within the same repertoire and still being able to use the ideas and concepts that I am going to be sharing here.   For that, I felt the Italian is the perfect weapon against the ever solid @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  systems.    This course is the first part of the complete 1.e4 repertoire, covers all the options for Black after 1...e5, which is Black's main and most challenging response against our 1.e4. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { This being a Lifetime Repertoire, I also discuss all possible and impossible gambits and oddities @@StartBracket@@to the extent that  2...d5?  and even  2...Qe7?  are covered@@EndBracket@@ and also, obviously, the more respectable openings, such as the Philidor,  2...d6  , and the Petroff,  2...Nf6  , are covered.   Against the Petroff, I recommend 3.d4!? which I believe to be the most challenging way to play against this ever-solid opening.  2...Nf6  3.d4   I believe the Petroff players still take this move less seriously than  3.Nxe5  , something that they will certainly regret once they face us.  3...Nxe4  4.Bd3  d5  5.Nxe5  Nd7  6.Nc3!  This is the system I advocate against the main line of the Petroff. The pawn structure becomes very imbalanced right away and a world of strategic nuances awaits you in the chapters dedicated to the Petroff. } 3. Bc4 { The Italian, though at this point it is not yet clear, whether we go for something forcing or the fundamental Italian, which is what I recommend.  The fundamental Italian is experiencing a renaissance already for quite a few years and there are two reasons for that - the negative one and the positive one.   The negative reason is that the Spanish  3.Bb5  , which has been the way to go at the highest level for decades, started experiencing serious issues.   Besides the infamous Berlin  3.Bb5  Nf6  , theory also started expanding in all sorts of directions:   • The Open Spanish  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Nxe4   • and the Archangelsk  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  b5  6.Bb3  Bb7  are more alive than ever.   • The Marshall  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  O-O  8.c3  d5  has also never left.    While the Spanish remains a critical way to go, at this point players are often wondering what exactly they are hoping for when placing the bishop on b5, as all of Black's options are equally repelling.  The positive reason, on the other hand, is that it turned out that while the greatest theoreticians have been banging their heads against the Spanish wall, the Italian, which has been neglected, offers at the very least just as large a scope of ideas.  As the engines got stronger, around five years ago, there has been a major reassessment of many positions and positional factors that we encounter in the Italian. It turned out that places where people used to stop their analysis, were just the starting points. In some openings, having the space advantage in the center was overrated, while it was underrated in others. That pointless-looking queenside expansions can have a long-term effect on the rest of the board and that the pawn structure should not be taken out of context as piece activity is often a more important factor.  On a broader scale, the turning point was the humbling realization that the top chess players, the trendsetters, don't know everything about the opening theory and that we all have a lot to learn from the computer, more than we could have previously imagined. That 'it looks fine' is no longer a good point to stop the analysis if the engine is screaming numbers.  The humility and the open-mindedness are what has pushed the top players towards the fundamental Italian and in this course, I will try to give you a taste for the kind of strategic depth and tactical possibilities the opening has to offer. } 3... Bc5 { 3...Nf6  This allows  4.Ng5  , which many fear, but that is more of a one-trick pony @@StartBracket@@pun intended@@EndBracket@@, compared to  4.d3  , as I believe once Black prepares for these forced lines, it is relatively easy to neutralize, as the scope of our possibilities is significantly smaller down those lines.   Against us, though, the  3...Nf6  move order is more flexible, but many of the players who go for ...Bc5-setups will play  3...Bc5  already here.   3...Nf6  4.d3  Here I obviously cover all of the options. Besides the ...Bc5-setup, there is the more modest and solid 4...Be7, but also the trendy fianchetto systems with ...h7-h6+g7-g5 and ...h7-h6+g7-g6.  The sidelines like the risky 4...d5 are also covered of course! } 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 { Followed by 6.O-O is the core of our repertoire.  Our setup is then somewhat dependent on our opponent’s choice, but in the long run, in many of the systems, we will eventually prepare the central push d3-d4. Conceptually speaking, the idea is to prepare and mobilize and then once fully ready go for the clash in the center. I believe this is a good way to play chess. } *

