 van Foreest. It turns out that capturing the d3-pawn leads to some complications and more importantly, these complications seem to lead to unpleasant positions for Black.  By now there are a few dozen high-level games on this topic and there is still no consensus on how exactly Black is supposed to neutralize White's initiative. First Black has to choose, to capture the pawn or not to. } 11... Qxd3 { Capturing the pawn is the most direct way to go. } 12. Nxe5 { The complications are clearly about to start. Black is once again facing a tough choice: does he want to sit it out in a worse endgame after  12...Bxd1  , retreat with  12...Qf5  or try his luck with the crazy-looking  12...Qg3  ?. } 12... Qf5 { The best move. The queen simply defends the h5-bishop and also hits the f2-pawn, forcing White to retreat. } 13. Nef3 { We have traded our central pawns and Black appears to be doing quite well, but suddenly there is a very unpleasant threat of g2-g4. Black has a choice, mainly between allowing it and sacrificing on g4 or go into hiding. } 13... Rad8 { The most played move. It is doing a good job preparing a piece sac on g4, but unlike  13...Rfe8  and  13...Rae8  , it doesn't force the g4-push, as we have a good alternative in  @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/ppp2ppp/1nn5/2b2q1b/8/1BP2N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qe2  . } 14. Qe2 { After  14.g4  Bxg4  15.hxg4  Qxg4+  16.Kh1  Qh3+  17.Nh2  Bd6!  18.f4  Bxf4  Black already regained 3 pawns and still has a very active position - a better version of 13...Rfe8/13...Rae8 lines. White is able to reach a roughly equal endgame after  19.Re2  followed by Qf1 and the game Michalik-Shirov was drawn.   14.Qe2!  is more testing. White grabs control over the e-file and reinforces the threat of g2-g4, as well as Ne4!?. } 14... Qc8 { A very logical and popular retreat. Black walks out of g2-g4 and prepares ...Rfe8.   Weaker is  14...Qd7?!  as after  15.Ne4!  Rfe8  there is  16.Nxc5!  hitting that queen. } 15. Ne4 { I believe this move has not yet exhausted its resources, but Magnus Carlsen played the clever  15.Qb5!?  Nd7  16.Nh4!  a6  17.Qf1!  and posed problems to Wesley So.   Black should play  17...g5!  according to the engines,  but it wasn't surprising to see Wesley play the human  17...Be7  only to end up worse after  18.Nf5!  .   After  15.Ne4  Black is at a crossroads. He can play the natural  15...Rfe8  , but also  15...Rde8!?  has its points, keeping f7 better protected. Other than that, there is the simple  15...Be7  and the sophisticated  15...Nd7!?  .  I don't think we need to go too deep into all of those moves, but we should know how to handle the position for the first few moves, to develop our pieces in the most accurate way, making sure that Black doesn't get an easy life. } 15... Rde8 { Vidit has played this one twice. The idea is to make sure there won't be any sorcery happening around the f7-square, unlike the stuff that we can see in the 15...Rfe8 line.  On the other hand, now only one of the Black's rooks is active. } 16. Bf4 { Following in the footsteps of Praggnanandhaa, the boy seems to be aware of quite some theory in his Italian! } 16... Bg6 17. Nfd2 { We have to retreat, as  17.Nfg5  no longer works with f7-pawn being so well protected. } 17... Nd7 { Here little Prag played the aggressive  18.h4  , but since that aggression without the active knight on g5 led nowhere, I propose to improve with a slow but very poisonous new idea. } 18. Qf1 { Our plan is simple: we want to follow this up with a couple of more retreats, Kh1, Bh2 and then get ready to strike with f2-f4 if a knight shows up on e5 and if not, we can always activate our a1-rook, either by means of Rad1 or the thematic a2-a4 push.  White enjoys a bit of an edge here and Black is yet to fully neutralize our opening initiative, which is also confirmed by the engines, that just like humans, seem to value good piece coordination.  Note, how still, despite so many efforts, breaks and manoeuvres, Black still has got the c6-knight restricted by our c3-pawn - his eternal issue. } *

