1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 { The ...Bc5 Italian can also be reached via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d3  . } 5... d6 6. O-O a6 { This is the traditional way of playing the Italian. Black gives room to the bishop on c5 and creates a positional threat of ...Na5, now that the b5-square is taken. } 7. a4 { White has to address the ...Na5 threat with the traditional move  7.Bb3  or the modern  7.a4!  .   After  7.Bb3  White would play Nbd2, h2-h3 and Re1, intending to bring the knight to g3 with Nd2-f1-g3. Black found different setups that are acceptable against this.   The topical  7.a4!?  preserves the light-squared bishop too, while it also gains space on the queenside - a factor that engines taught us to appreciate more and more. } 7... Ba7 { For us, it doesn't matter whether Black starts with  7...O-O  or  7...Ba7  , but most players choose this one, as it works better against  8.Bg5  . } 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 { This is important. While there are many different orders, combining Re1 and Nbd2 without h2-h3 would be a serious inaccuracy as it allows ...Ng4!:  9.Nbd2  Ng4!  10.Re2  Kh8!  11.h3  f5!  and Black is having quite some fun at our expense. } 9... h6 10. Nbd2 Re8 { This, intending to play ...Be6 and then recapture with the rook, without doubling the pawns is probably the most solid setup one can play against the Italian.  Black wants to trade White's active Italian bishop without creating any weaknesses, hoping to then slowly deal with the issue of the c6-knight, but eventually transferring it over to g6 via e7, with or without the ...d6-d5-break.  White in his turn will push b4 and hope to claim a small but lasting edge, thanks to more space on the queenside and the better-arranged knights. } 11. b4 { This is generally more flexible than starting with  11.Nf1  here. White anyway wants to grab space on the queenside, while the move Nf1 is only one of the options down the road on move 13, as we shall see. } 11... Be6 12. Bxe6 Rxe6 13. Bb2 { I have played this cunning move on various occasions and I have chosen this as my main recommendation.  It is not clear whether the bishop is that well placed on b2 at the moment, as the a1-h8-diagonal is rather closed, but the main purpose of this move is prophylaxis. We are basically bracing for the ...d5-break, after which we intend to start some complications, including an eventual c3-c4 and our bishop activating itself.  The bishop also does a good job defending the c3-pawn in these ...d5-variations and finally, if the c6-knight chooses to go to g6, we can then push c3-c4 and eventually also d3-d4, when our bishop will start looking quite good on the long diagonal. } 13... b5 { Stopping b4-b5 once and for all. This move has once been played by So against me, but it doesn't solve all of Black's problems. } 14. d4 { I knew that this pawn sac is good. } 14... Re8 { Wesley has gone for the solid option. } 15. axb5 axb5 16. Qe2 { I managed to find this good move, hitting the b5-pawn. } 16... exd4 17. Qxb5 dxc3 { This is what Wesley has played. } 18. Bxc3 Ne5 { There are a lot of simplifications, but White does keep some of that opening advantage if precise play. } 19. Nxe5 { This would have led to a good position.   I was too clever with  19.Qb7?!  and the game was eventually drawn in the Croatian Classical GCT event 2019.   19...dxe5  20.Nf3  Bd4  This move bothered me.  21.Rad1  Forcing the complications.   21...Nxe4  22.Rxe4  Bxf2+  23.Kxf2  Qxd1  24.Bxe5!  Keeping the harmony.   24.Rxe5  allows  24...Qc2+  with some counterplay.  24...Ra2+  25.Kg3  I didn't assess this position correctly in my game against Wesley, but actually, White is just crushing, thanks to much more active pieces and in fact the safer king! } *

