th  9.Nd5!  and there no longer is ...Nb4 after  9...Bxd5  10.exd5  .   Also including  8.a5  a6  is an idea and only then  9.Bd2  , but I like inviting the option of @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1bpp1/2np1n1p/4p3/P1B1P3/2NP1N2/1PPB1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Na5  9.Ba2  c5?!  . } 8... Na5 { The idea of ...Na5 and ...c7-c5 is surprisingly dubious here, with the pawn being on h6. } 9. Ba2 c5 { Better is to retreat with  9...Nc6  , but people usually don't play chess like that. } 10. Nh4 { Using the flaw in the little move ...h7-h6. Now suddenly Ng6 is a threat and ...h6 turns out to be a weakening of the kingside. } 10... Nxe4 { is a typical way of meeting Nh4, but Black should always see beyond winning the pawn, as it can often get tricky when trading off the f6-knight, which often is a crucial defender. } 11. Nxe4 Bxh4 12. Qh5 { White starts a strong attack, while Black is totally uncoordinated with the knight on a5 and the bishop on h4. Bxh6, as well as f4, are coming up next. } *

